uk.co.strangeskies.reflection

Class ExecutableMember<O,R>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.co.strangeskies.reflection.ExecutableMember<O,R>
  • Type Parameters:
    O - The receiver type of the executable.
    R - The return type of the executable.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    TypeMember<O>

    public class ExecutableMember<O,R>
extends Object
implements TypeMember<O>

    A type safe wrapper around Executable instances, with proper handling of generic methods, and methods on generic classes. Instances of this class can be created from instances of Executable directly from over(Executable) and its overloads, or using the TypeToken.resolveConstructorOverload(List) and TypeToken.resolveMethodOverload(String, List) methods on TypeToken instances.

    executable members may be created over types which mention inference variables, or even over inference variables themselves.

      • withOwnerType

        public <U extends O> ExecutableMember<U,? extends R> withOwnerType(TypeToken<U> type)
        Derive a new instance of ExecutableMember with the given receiver type. This will resolve any overriding Executable to determine a new return type if necessary.

        The new ExecutableMember will always have a receiver type which is as or more specific than both the current receiver type and the given type. This means that the new receiver will be assignment compatible with the given type, but if the given type contains wildcards or inference variables which are less specific that those implied by the current receiver type, new type arguments will be inferred in their place, or further bounds may be added to them.

        Specified by:
        withOwnerType in interface TypeMember<O>
        Type Parameters:
        U - The new receiver type. The raw type of this type must be a subtype of the raw type of the current receiver type.
        Parameters:
        type - The new receiver type. The raw type of this type must be a subtype of the raw type of the current receiver type.
        Returns:
        A new ExecutableMember compatible with the given receiver type.

        The new receiver type will not be effectively more specific than the intersection type of the current receiver type and the given type. That is, any type which can be assigned to both the given type and the current receiver type, will also be assignable to the new type.

      • withInferredType

        public <U> ExecutableMember<O,U> withInferredType(TypeToken<U> targetType,
                                                  TypeToken<?>... arguments)
        Derive a new ExecutableMember fulfilling two conditions.
        • Firstly, that the result be assignment compatible with the given target type.
        • Secondly, that the arguments are compatible in either a loose invocation context, or failing that, a variable arity invocation context.

        This method uses the same type inference algorithm as the Java language, and so will only fail in those cases where the Java compiler would have failed to infer a type.

        Type Parameters:
        U - The derived ExecutableMember must be assignment compatible with this type.
        Parameters:
        targetType - The derived ExecutableMember must be assignment compatible with this type.
        arguments - The derived ExecutableMember must be loose invocation compatible, or failing that variable arity compatible, with the given arguments.
        Returns:
        A new ExecutableMember compatible with the given target type and parameters, and which has more specific arguments, type arguments, and return type than the receiving ExecutableMember.

      • invoke

        public R invoke(O receiver,
                Object... arguments)
        Invoke the wrapped Executable on the given receiver and with the given parameters. The receiver will be ignored for static methods or constructors. Variable arity invocation is not attempted.

        Due to erasure of the types of the arguments, there is a limit to what type checking can be performed at runtime. For type safe invocation, wrap arguments in TypedObject instances and use an overload of invokeSafely(Object, TypedObject...) instead.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.

      • invoke

        public R invoke(O receiver,
                List<? extends Object> arguments)
        Invoke the wrapped Executable on the given receiver and with the given parameters. The receiver will be ignored for static methods or constructors. Variable arity invocation is not attempted.

        Due to erasure of the types of the arguments, there is a limit to what type checking can be performed at runtime. For type safe invocation, wrap arguments in TypedObject instances and use an overload of invokeSafely(Object, TypedObject...) instead.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.

      • invokeSafely

        public R invokeSafely(O receiver,
                      TypedObject<?>... arguments)

        As invoke(Object, Object...), but with arguments passed with their exact types, meaning full type checking can be performed at runtime. Also, here it is possible to determine whether the invocation is intended to be variable arity, and if so an attempt is made to invoke as such.

        If the expected parameter types of this executable member contain inference variables or type variable captures, an attempt will be made to satisfy their bounds according to the given argument types.

        Parameters:
        receiver - The receiving object for the invocation. This parameter will be ignored in the case of a constructor invocation or other static method invocation.
        arguments - The typed argument list for the invocation.
        Returns:
        The result of the invocation.

      • resolveApplicableExecutableMembers

        public static <T,R> Set<? extends ExecutableMember<? super T,? extends R>> resolveApplicableExecutableMembers(Set<? extends ExecutableMember<? super T,? extends R>> candidates,
                                                                                                              List<? extends TypeToken<?>> parameters)
        Find the set of all given overload candidates which are applicable to invocation with the given parameters. Strict applicability is considered first, then if no candidates are found loose applicability is considered, then if still no candidates are found, variable arity applicability is considered.
        Type Parameters:
        T - The receiving type of the given executable members.
        R - The return type of the given executable members.
        Parameters:
        candidates - The candidates for which we wish to determine applicability.
        parameters - The parameters representing the invocation for which we wish to determine applicability.
        Returns:
        The set of all given overload candidates which are most applicable to invocation with the given parameters.

      • resolveMostSpecificExecutableMember

        public static <T,R> ExecutableMember<? super T,? extends R> resolveMostSpecificExecutableMember(Collection<? extends ExecutableMember<? super T,? extends R>> candidates)
        Find which of the given overload candidates is the most specific according to the rules described by the Java 8 language specification.

        If no single most specific candidate can be found, the method will throw a TypeException.

        Type Parameters:
        T - The receiving type of the given executable members.
        R - The return type of the given executable members.
        Parameters:
        candidates - The candidates from which to select the most specific.
        Returns:
        The most specific of the given candidates.
